@@eThe Umbral: The Necessary Absence@@N

@@dFrom a document found pinned to the door of the Midgaard Hall@@N
@@dof Records. No author claimed. The ink was cold to the touch.@@N

They are shadow given permanent form. Not darkness-worshippers, not
cursed, not phantoms — @@epeople@@N, whose bodies absorbed the
anti-light of the @@rBlack Sun Shard@@N over generations of habitation
in the spaces adjacent to it. The change was slow. The change was
thorough. The change cannot be reversed, and they have not asked
for it to be.

An Umbral is difficult to perceive in shadow. The eye @@yslides off
them@@N — not invisibility, but a quality of presence that resists
direct observation. They are lighter than their frames suggest, as
though part of their substance exists somewhere the scales cannot
measure. In full light they are visible, solid, present. In darkness
they are @@esomething else@@N — not absent, but adjacent to absence.

Their philosophy is built on a single principle: @@ynecessary
absence@@N. What is not present shapes reality as powerfully as
what is. The silence between words carries meaning. The gap in
the record reveals what was removed. The shadow defines the shape
of the light. The Umbral do not consider themselves diminished.
They consider themselves @@eevidence@@N.

They maintain the @@eshadow-archives@@N — repositories of records,
testimony, and documentation that the institutions of Midgaard and
Kowloon prefer not to have accessible. Not stolen records. Records
that were discarded, sealed, or conveniently lost. The Umbral
collected what the powerful threw away and @@ypreserved it in the
dark@@N.

The @@eGloamvault@@N beneath Midgaard is their oldest known
habitation. They were there before the city. When the first human
builders laid foundations, they found Umbral stonework already in
place — older, deeper, and @@dquite clearly not interested in
being excavated@@N. The city was built on top of them. This is,
the Umbral note, @@ya pattern@@N.

They do not campaign for recognition. They do not protest their
exclusion from civic record. They simply @@econtinue to exist@@N
in the spaces that the record does not acknowledge, holding the
documents that the record does not contain.

@@dWhat you cannot see still has weight.@@N
@@dWhat you will not record is still true.@@N
